{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013EL77ChDcxQxM38MdW9grW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"es-cluster-0 is trying to discover the master but can't find the other nodes! It's only seeing itself. This is a network issue - it can't reach es-cluster-1 and es-cluster-2.\n\nThe problem: when I applied `services.yaml` and changed the `es-cluster` headless service selector to `app=es-cluster` (from `app=elasticsearch`), then changed it back to `app=elasticsearch`, and now the pods have MIXED labels:\n\nAfter my --cascade=orphan and labeling:\n- es-cluster-0: `app=es-cluster` (just labeled this)\n- es-cluster-1: `app=es-cluster`\n- es-cluster-2: `app=es-cluster`\n- The `es-cluster` headless service selector: `app=elasticsearch`\n\nSince all 3 pods now have `app=es-cluster` but the headless service selects `app=elasticsearch`, the DNS for `es-cluster-0.es-cluster`, `es-cluster-1.es-cluster`, etc. doesn't resolve! That's why es-cluster-0 can't discover the other nodes. But wait, es-cluster-1 and es-cluster-2 joined the cluster successfully, so something else is going on here.\n\nLet me trace back the timeline: I patched the headless service selector back to `app=elasticsearch` before I relabeled the pods. At that point, the pods still had their original `app=elasticsearch` labels, so DNS worked and the nodes could discover each other. Then I labeled everything with `app=es-cluster`, which broke the selector match between the service and the pods. So es-cluster-1 and es-cluster-2 must have already joined the cluster during that window when the labels aligned with the service selector.\n\nNow es-cluster-0 is a fresh pod trying to bootstrap, and it can't resolve the DNS names for the other nodes because the headless service selector is still pointing to `app=elasticsearch` while the pods are labeled `app=es-cluster`. I need to patch the service selector to match the current pod labels so DNS resolut